ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.0af9881e-6c56-4f7b-bf54-0734446f6ceb.description=
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:
isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.
ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.180b18e3-2565-4422-ba33-ecb431261dac.description=
Invokes web service methods.  This operation should not be used directly\!  Please use the wizard to build flows that use this operation.

Inputs\:
xmlTemplate - The template of the soap request to make.
inputMap - A map used to map between template names and user-friendly names. The tamplate names are pipe-delimited xpaths of the xmltemplate location, with a numerical element for lists.
url - The url to post to. 
header_SOAPAction - The SOAPAction http header field, defined by many web services for indicating the intent of the request
wswAuthenticationType - The authentication type to use for the username and password input. http is default (Uses http authentication), other options are 'ntlm', 'ws-security digest' and 'ws-security text' WARNING\: ws-security text transmits passwords in clear-text
WSSecuritySignRequest - true or false, should the SOAP request be signed using WS-Security.
WSSecurityEncryptRequest - true or false, should the entire SOAP request be signed using WS-Security
WSSecurityTimestampRequest - true or false, should the Timestamp attribute be added to the WS-Security header
WSSecurityKeystore - keystore to use for encrypting and signing requests.
WSSecurityKeystoreType - The type of WSSecurityKeystore.
WSSecurityKeystorePassword - The password for WSSecurityKeystore.
contentType - Value to be used in the Content-Type http header
characterSet - The characterSet for HTTP Get request and response. Default is UTF-8.
username - The username to use for authenticating with the web service. For NTLM authentication, the required format is domain\user.
password - The password to use for authenticating with the web service
trustAllRoots - Enables weak security over SSL. A SSH certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it. valid options are\: true/false.
useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. valid options are\: true/false.
usesJSON - Use JSON arrays for the SOAP Request for all Array types. valid options are\: true/false.
timeout - a timeout after which the connection should be terminated, or 0 for no timeout.
proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the web service.
proxyPort - A port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - A username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - A password to use when connecting to the proxy.
keystore - the path to the keystore to use for SSL Client Certificates when using http authentication
keystorePassword - the password for the keystore when using http authentication
ICONCLUDE_WSW_VERSION - This value is used internally by the operation
returnXMLRequest - If this input is set to true, a new output named rawXMLRequest is returned from the operation which contains the text of the SOAP request that will be sent. This can be very valuable in troubleshooting.

Any additional inputs that follow these are added by the Web Service Wizard, and they are specific to the particular web service method being called.

Responses\:
success - SOAP request completed successfully.
failure - something went wrong.

Returns\:
document - raw XML response
documentStripped - raw XML response stripped of namespaces for ease in parsing with XML XPath operations
jsonStripped - raw XML response stripped of namespaces for ease in parsing with JSON operations, input usesJSON must be set to true for this to be populated.

Notes\:
If you add new step-level inputs with the name header_, where  is the name of an html header, then that html header will be set to the given value in the HTTP request.
ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.1a10735c-73a1-469f-a3b6-8ffff405d131.description=

Displays a message to the user.

Inputs\:
  message - The message text to display
  title - The title on the message window. Defaults to "Status message".

Responses\:
  Always returns success.

Examples\:
  In order to display the message "Finished" to the user, go to the 
  detail screen for the input named "message" and change the Otherwise option
  from Prompt User to Use Constant.  Then enter the text "Finished" into the
  Constant Value field.

  References to flow variables in the Contant Value field are expanded so that
  the text may be dynamic.  Flow variable references are of the form
  ${variable}.  For example, the text\:
     ${count} systems were modified 
  could be used to display a message about the number of systems that were
  repaired, whose value is in the flow variable "count".

  When the message is displayed, it will properly render any embedded html
  tags, which permits creating messages with more advanced formatting.  For 
  example to display a message in italics you could use\:
    This is important
  or to display a message in red\:
    This is really  important

  You can create messages that contain multiple lines by entering a multiple
  line message in the Constant Value field, or by using HTML 
 tags for line
  breaks.  Note that \n characters are displayed literally and are not used for
  creating multiple lines.
ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.24d93367-2274-4680-b340-fc7cdb499db5.description=Attempts to acquire the specified lock, and sleeps until the lock is available. 
Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.
   timeout - The maximum number of seconds this flow will run for.
  seconds - The number of seconds to sleep for between each attempt at acquiring the lock.

Responses\:
   success - if the lock has been successfully acquired.
   failure - if the lock could not be acquired.

Result\:
   Code - 0 if the operation succeeds, 1 otherwise.

Notes\:
1) The locks acquired by this operation are not reentrant. This means that 
   once a lock is acquired by a run, all subsequent attempts at acquiring 
   the same lock by the same run (or any other run) will fail.

2) Once a run terminates, all the locks that were acquired during its execution
   are automatically released.
ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.57f5d097-521b-46ae-a05a-373b8cab8310.description=Releases a lock with an id given by the value of the lockId input. 
Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.

Responses\:
   success - the only response returned.

Results\:
   there are no results.

Notes\:
1) The operation only releases locks acquired by the current run. 
   It cannot release another run's locks.

2) The operation succeeds whether or not there is a lock held 
   by the current run with the supplied id.
ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.73dca821-f5d4-408b-b457-baba84772b64.description=
Adds a flow variable into the local context (available to itself and child flows only)

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the flow variable to use
myValue - the value to assign the flow variable

Responses\:
success - assigned the flow variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, $myValue];

ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.b14fe22b-f92f-44cf-b1fb-c200a296e9ed.description=Takes a reference to XML (in the form of a String) and the specified XPath Query is run against the XML and the result returned. The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) organization provides the XPath specification (http\://www.w3.org). 
Inputs\:
xml               	- The XML (in the form of a String)
xpathQuery 	- The XpathQuery that is wanted to be run.
delimiter	- The delimiter used to separate values in the returnResult list. The default is a comma.

Result Value\:
returnResult - The result of the operation. If multiple XPaths are defined then this will add the delimiter between each value. There is no final delimiter.

ff9425b0-d7dd-48f1-aab6-d4ed83cd0044.da64418f-c615-4044-ad27-afd9451f2cc7.description=This operation runs a SQL command. Inputs\: DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of the database server. DbType - The type of database to connect to. Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2 and Custom. Default value\: Oracle Username - The username to use when connecting to the database. Password - The password to use when connecting to the database. instance - The name instance (for MSSQL Server). Leave it blank for default instance. DbPort - The port to connect to. Default values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000. Database - The name of the database. authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL) Default value\: sql dbClass - The classname of the JDBC driver to use. dbURL - The url required to load up the driver and make your connection. Command - The command to execute. timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. When the default value is used, there is no limit on the amount of time allowed for a running command to complete. Default value\: 0 databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. For more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description. Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true resultSetType - the result set type. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE. Default value\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY resultSetConcurrency - the result set concurrency. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY, CONCUR_UPDATABLE Default value\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "Command completed successfully" message if the operation succeeded, or a failure message otherwise. outputText - The return result of SQL command. updateCount - The update count of the command executed. Responses\: success - The command was executed successfully. failure - Failed to execute the command. Note\: 1. Check the JDBC folder description for details on how to load database connectors. 2. In case of using subprograms like (GET_LINE, GET_LINES, NEW_LINE, PUT, PUT_LUNE) from DBMS_OUTPUT package, the DBMS_OUTPUT.ENABLE() declaration should be used before of these calls.
